"'''Honesty'''" is a song by American singer-songwriter [[Billy Joel]]. [[Columbia Records]] released the song as the second single from his album sixth studio album ''[[52nd Street (album)|52nd Street]]'' (1978) in 1979. "Honesty" was solely written by Joel, while production was handled by [[Phil Ramone]]. The song was not included on any of Joel's US released compilation packages; however, it appears on the Dutch edition as well as the aforementioned Japanese edition of ''[[Greatest Hits (Billy Joel albums)|Greatest Hits Volume 2]]'', instead of "[[Don't Ask Me Why (Billy Joel song)|Don't Ask Me Why]]" (1980). "Honesty" is a [[piano ballad]] that talks about the inherent lack of same. 

The song received mostly positive reviews from music critics who generally praised its lyrics and the piano instrumentation. It also received comparisons to other songs by Joel. It reached number twenty-four on the [[Billboard Hot 100|''Billboard'' Hot 100]] chart in the US, becoming the album's third consecutive top forty hit. It was certified gold by [[Recording Industry Association of Japan]] for [[ringtone]] [[music download|download]] sales of over 100,000 units. Joel performed the song live several times along with [[Elton John]] and later with [[Bryan Adams]]. "Honesty" has been covered and sampled by various artists, most notably by American [[contemporary R&B|R&B]] recording artist, [[Beyonc<U+00E9> Knowles]].

==Background and composition==
"Honesty" was solely written by Billy Joel while production was handled by Phil Ramone.<ref name="Booklet" /> It is the second song from his sixth studio album ''[[52nd Street (album)|52nd Street]]'' (1978).<ref name="Booklet">{{cite album-notes|title=52nd Street|albumlink=52nd Street (album)|artist=Billy Joel|year=1978|notestitle=|first=Billy |last=Joel|authorlink=Billy Joel|coauthors=|format=Compact Disc|publisher=Family Productions/[[Columbia Records]]}}</ref> The song was also included on South Korean and Japanese edition of Joel's 1985 compilation ''Greatest Hits Volume 2'' as one of the [[bonus track]]s.<ref name="greatest" /> The song wasn't included on any of Joel's US released compilation packages; however, it appears on the Dutch edition as well as the aforementioned Japanese edition of ''[[Greatest Hits (Billy Joel albums)|Greatest Hits Volume 2]]'', instead of "[[Don't Ask Me Why (Billy Joel song)|Don't Ask Me Why]]" (1980).<ref name="greatest">Sources for the Dutch and Japanese editions of ''[[Greatest Hits (Billy Joel albums)|Greatest Hits Volume 2]]'':
*{{cite album-notes |title=Greatest Hits Volume 2 |artist=[[Billy Joel]] |publisherid= |year=1985 |format=Dutch Edition |publisher=[[Columbia Records]]}}
*{{cite album-notes |title=Greatest Hits Volume 2 |artist=Billy Joel |publisherid= |year=1985 |format=Japanese Edition |publisher=Columbia Records}}
*{{cite album-notes |title=Greatest Hits Volume 2 |artist=Billy Joel |publisherid= |year=1985 |format=South Korean Edition |publisher=Columbia Records}}
</ref> [[David Spinozza]] plays the acoustic guitar in the song, [[Liberty DeVitto]] plays the [[drum kit|drums]] and Robert Freedman the [[Horn (instrument)|horn]] and string [[orchestration]].<ref name="Booklet" /> 

"Honesty" is a [[piano ballad]] with [[synthesizer]] [[Ornament (music)|embellishments]].<ref name="Bielen" /> It opens with "sad and tender" [[piano]] chords.<ref name="Bielen" /> According to Ken Bielen in his book ''The Words and Music of Billy Joel'', Liberty DeVitto's drums and [[Crash cymbal|cymbal crashes]], remind listeners that "the track is a predecessor of the [[power ballad]]s of the [[1980s]] and [[1990s]]".<ref name="Bielen" /> It talks about the inherent lack of same even in the closest of relationships.<ref>{{cite news| url=http://news.google.com/newspapers?id=Utk8AAAAIBAJ&sjid=Hy4MAAAAIBAJ&pg=2352,1519769&dq=billy+joel+honesty+song&hl=en|title=Latest Joel, Marison cuts not up to snuff|work=[[Bangor Daily News]]|publisher=Bangor Publishing Company|date=November 3, 1978|first=Rich|last=Tozier|page=147|accessdate=August 24, 2011}}</ref> In the song Joel sings the lines "Honesty is such a lonely word".<ref>{{cite news| url=http://www.heraldsun.com.au/sport/lack-of-trust-hurts-nfl-talks/story-e6frfglf-1226019750816|title=Lack of trust hurts NFL talks|date=March 11, 2011|first=Alex|last=Marvez|work=[[Herald Sun]]|publisher=[[The Herald and Weekly Times]]. News Corporation|accessdate=August 24, 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.telegraph.co.uk/sport/rugbyunion/international/wales/8839352/Rugby-World-Cup-2011-Well-done-Warren-Gatland-you-honestly-cost-Wales-the-World-Cup.html|title=Rugby World Cup 2011: Well done Warren Gatland, you honestly cost Wales the World Cup|work=[[The Daily Telegraph]]|publisher=[[Telegraph Media Group]]|first=Matthew|last=Norman|date=October 20, 2011|accessdate=March 8, 2012}}</ref> Joel further sings about wearing his heart on his sleeve in "Honesty".<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.americansongwriter.com/2012/02/tommy-womack-now-what/|title=Tommy Womack: Now What!|work=[[American Songwriter]]|first=Rick|last=Moore|date=February 20, 2012|accessdate=March 8, 2012}}</ref> According to Chuck Klosterman of ''[[The New York Times]]'', "[the song] implies that the only way you can tell that someone really cares about you is if they tell you you're bad."<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.nytimes.com/2002/09/15/magazine/the-stranger.html?pagewanted=all&src=pm|title=The Stranger|work=[[The New York Times]]|publisher=[[The New York Times Company]]|first=Chuck|last=Klosterman|date=September 15, 2002|accessdate=May 30, 2012}}</ref> "[[Leningrad (song)|Leningrad]]" (1989), a song by Joel's eleventh studio album, ''[[Storm Front (album)|Storm Front]]'' has been compared to "Honesty".<ref>{{cite news| url=http://www.nytimes.com/1989/10/18/arts/the-pop-life-091389.html|title=The Pop Life|work=The New York Times|publisher=The New York Times Company|first=Stephen|last=Holden|date=October 18, 1989|accessdate=August 24, 2011}}</ref> According to the sheet music published on the website Musicnotes.com by [[Faber Music]], "Honesty" is a [[pop rock]] and [[classical rock]] song written in the key of [[B-flat major|B<U+266D> major]].<ref name="sheet">{{cite web|first=Billy|last=Joel|title=Billy Joel - Honesty Sheet Music (Digital Download)|year=1978|publisher=Musicnotes.com. [[Faber Music]]|id=MN0043571|accessdate=August 24, 2011}}</ref> The song is set in common time and performed in a slow tempo of 80 beats per minute.<ref name="sheet" /> Joel{{'s}} vocals range from the note of [[B (musical note)|B<sub>b3</sub>]] to [[A (musical note)|A<sub>4</sub>]].<ref name="sheet" />

==Reception==
While reviewing ''52nd Street'' [[Stephen Thomas Erlewine]] of the website [[Allmusic]] noted that "Honesty" was one of Joel's best songs.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.allmusic.com/album/52nd-street-r10421/review|title=52nd Street - Billy Joel|publisher=[[Allmusic]]. [[Rovi Corporation]]|first=Stephen|last=Thomas Erlewine|authorlink=Stephen Thomas Erlewine|accessdate=December 20, 2011}}</ref> Timothy White of ''[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]'' magazine called the song a pensive pop hit.<ref>{{cite journal|url=http://books.google.mk/books?id=ZwgEAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA14&dq=Honesty+Billy+Joel&hl=en&sa=X&ei=-wpZT-qSBZODtgfBtPiFDA&redir_esc=y#v=onepage&q=Honesty%20Billy%20Joel&f=false|title=A portrait of The Artist|work=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|publisher=[[Prometheus Global Media]]|first=Timothy|last=White|date=December 3, 1994|accessdate=March 8, 2012|page=14|issue=|issn=0006-2510}}</ref> A writer of ''[[Rolling Stone]]'' felt that "The sweet music of 'Honesty' is sabotaged by trite lyrics".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rollingstone.com/music/artists/billy-joel/albumguide|title=Billy Joel: Album Guide|work=[[Rolling Stone]]|publisher=[[Jann Wenner|Wenner Media]]|accessdate=March 8, 2012}}</ref> ''[[The Phoenix (newspaper)|The Phoenix]]''{{'}}s Michael Lawson noted that the song was "well suited for middle-of-the-road tastes".<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.google.com/newspapers?id=iIRkAAAAIBAJ&sjid=xn8NAAAAIBAJ&pg=4996,3508140&dq=billy+joel+52nd+street+honesty&hl=en|title=Billy Joel - 52nd Street, Columbia|work=[[The Phoenix (newspaper)|The Phoenix]]|publisher=[[Phoenix Media/Communications Group]]|first=Michael|last=Lawson|page=69|date=November 25, 1978|accessdate=April 8, 2012}}</ref> According to Ken Bielen, "'Honesty' is a plea for truth, not only in romantic relationships but also from the politicians who affect our lives."<ref name="Bielen" /> Adam Graham of [[MTV News]] described the song as a "big ballad".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mtv.com/news/articles/1681557/american-idol-billy-joel-jessica-sanchez.jhtml|title='American Idol' Top 10 In A Billy Joel State Of Mind|publisher=[[MTV News]]. [[MTV Networks]]|first=Adam|last=Graham|date=March 21, 2012|accessdate=May 30, 2012}}</ref> The song was nominated in the category for [[Grammy Award for Song of the Year|Song of the Year]] at the [[22nd Grammy Awards]] held on February 27, 1980.<ref name="Grammy1980">{{cite web|url=http://news.google.com/newspapers?id=JcopAAAAIBAJ&sjid=LO4DAAAAIBAJ&pg=6870,4003315&dq|title=Grammy awards field a definite mixed bag|date=January 9, 1980|accessdate=April 14, 2012|page=70|work=[[The Spokesman-Review]]|publisher=[[Cowles Publishing Company]]|first=Yardena|last=Arar}}</ref>

"Honesty" peaked at number sixteen on the Canadian Singles Chart.<ref name="can" /> On July 28, 1979 the song debuted at number thirty one on the Dutch Top 40 which later become its peak position.<ref name="top100" /> The next week, the song fell seven positions placing at number thirty eight.<ref name="top100" /> However on August 11, 1979, "Honesty" charted at number thirty five before falling out of the chart the next week.<ref name="top100" /> In New Zealand, "Honesty" debuted at number forty seven, on June 10, 1979 and later peaked at number thirty eight. After its peak position, the song fell out of the chart.<ref name="nz" /> On the [[Billboard Hot 100|''Billboard'' Hot 100]] chart in the US, the song peaked at number twenty four.<ref name="bill" /><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rollingstone.com/music/artists/billy-joel/biography|title=Billy Joel: Biography|work=Rolling Stone|publisher=Wenner Media|first=Evan|last=Serpick|accessdate=March 8, 2012}}</ref> In May 2009, Joel's version was certified gold by [[Recording Industry Association of Japan]] for [[ringtone]] [[music download|download]] sales of over 100,000 units.<ref name="riajcertification0905">{{cite web| url=http://www.riaj.or.jp/data/others/chart/w090620.html <U+8CA1><U+56E3><U+6CD5><U+4EBA><U+3000><U+65E5><U+672C><U+30EC><U+30B3><U+30FC><U+30C9><U+5354><U+4F1A> > <U+5404><U+7A2E><U+7D71><U+8A08> > <U+6709><U+6599><U+97F3><U+697D><U+914D><U+4FE1><U+8A8D><U+5B9A> > 2009<U+5E74>5<U+6708>| title= (RIAJ - Statistics - Music Download Certification Awards - May 2009)| language=Japanese| publisher=[[Recording Industry Association of Japan]]| accessdate=April 20, 2010}}</ref>

==Live performances==
Joel performed the song with [[Elton John]] at [[Giants Stadium]] in [[East Rutherford, New Jersey|East Rutherford]], [[New Jersey]] in July, 1994. First, they sang "[[Your Song]]" (1970) by John and after that they performed "Honesty" while playing on the piano.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.nytimes.com/1994/07/25/arts/pop-review-elton-john-and-billy-joel-so-alike-so-different.html|title=POP REVIEW; Elton John and Billy Joel: So Alike, So Different|first=Neil|last=Strauss|date=July 25, 1994|work=The New York Times|publisher=The New York Times Company|accessdate=August 24, 2011}}</ref> "Honesty" was also performed by John and Joel on March, 29, 1995 in [[Rogers Centre|SkyDome]], [[Toronto]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://jam.canoe.ca/Music/Artists/J/Joel_Billy/ConcertReviews/2004/09/25/643762.html|title=Concert Review: SkyDome, Toronto - Mar 29, 1995|first=John|last=Sakamoto|date=April 30, 1995|accessdate=August 24, 2011|publisher=[[Jam!]]. [[Sun Media]]}}</ref> The same routine was performed in May, 1998 in [[Dublin]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.independent.ie/national-news/polished-piano-pair-serenade-fans-with-face-to-face-concert-446991.html|title=Polished piano pair serenade fans with face to face concert|work=[[Irish Independent]]|publisher=[[Independent News and Media]]|date=May 30, 1998|first=Niamh|last=Hooper|accessdate=August 24, 2011}}</ref> On July 31, 2006, Joel performed the song with Canadian rock singer-songwriter [[Bryan Adams]] in Colosseum, [[Rome]], [[Italy]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.contactmusic.com/news.nsf/story/joel-and-adams-team-up-for-free-concert_1004147|title=Joel And Adams Team Up For Free Concert|publisher=[[Contactmusic.com]]|date=August 1, 2006|accessdate=August 24, 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.foxnews.com/wires/2006Aug01/0,4670,ItalyColosseumConcert,00.html|title=Billy Joel, Bryan Adams Perform Free Show|date=August 1, 2006|publisher=[[Fox News Channel]]. [[News Corporation]]|author=The Associated Press|accessdate=August 24, 2011}}</ref>

