==Cover versions==
Belgian [[jazz]] musician, [[Toots Thielemans]], recorded a [[harmonica]] instrumental cover version of the song with a five-piece combo at Nippon Columbia's Grand Studio in Tokyo, Japan in 1979.<ref name="Bielen" /> "Honesty" has been particularly popular in South Korea and Japan for decades and covered by East Asian musicians including [[Hajime Mizoguchi]] on his album ''yours;tears'' (2007),<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cdjapan.co.jp/detailview.html?KEY=VPCD-81566|title=Hajime Mizoguchi - yours;tears|publisher=CD Japan|accessdate=December 21, 2011}}</ref> and [[K (singer)|K]] on his album ''[[The Timeless Collection Vol. 1]]'' (2007).<ref>{{cite album-notes|title=The Timeless Collection Vol. 1|albumlink=The Timeless Collection Vol. 1|artist=[[K (singer)|K]]|year=2007|publisher=[[Studioseven Recordings]]|format=Compact Disc}}</ref> In 1981, Mexican singer David Haro recorded under the title "Sinceridad" from the album ''Calido''.<ref>{{cite album-notes|title=Calido|artist=David Haro|year=1981|format=Compact Disc}}</ref> "From Marcy to Hollywood", a song by American rappers [[Jay-Z]], [[Memphis Bleek]] and [[Sauce Money]] from the soundtrack album ''[[The Players Club (soundtrack)|The Players Club]]'', (1998) featured a sample of "Honesty".<ref name="jayz">{{cite album-notes|title=The Players Club|albumlink=The Players Club (soundtrack)|artist=Jay-Z, Memphis Bleek and Sauce Money|year=1998|notestitle=|coauthors= |format=Compact Disc |publisher=Heavyweight/[[A&M Records|A&M]]}}</ref> During his audutions for [[Fox Broadcasting Company|Fox]]'s ''[[Glee (TV series)|Glee]]'', Canadian actor [[Cory Monteith]] sang "Honesty".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cbc.ca/news/arts/tv/story/2009/11/18/cory-monteith.html|title=Glee's song and dance all new for Cory Monteith|publisher=[[CBC.ca]]. 	[[Canadian Broadcasting Corporation]]|date=November 18, 2009|accessdate=March 8, 2012}}</ref> In 2010, Swedish singer [[Helen Sj<U+00F6>holm]] covered the song for her 2010 album ''[[Euforia <U+2013> Helen Sj<U+00F6>holm sjunger Billy Joel]]'' under the title "<U+00C4>rlighet".<ref>{{cite album-notes|title=Euforia <U+2013> Helen Sj<U+00F6>holm sjunger Billy Joel|albumlink=Euforia <U+2013> Helen Sj<U+00F6>holm sjunger Billy Joel|artist=[[Helen Sj<U+00F6>holm]]|year=2010|publisher=[[Universal Music Group]]|format=Compact Disc|publisherid=060252753381}}</ref> 

In March, 2012, [[American Idol (season 11)|eleventh season]] contestant of ''[[American Idol]]'', [[Hollie Cavanagh]], covered the song. Her performance received mixed reviews from the judges of the show, who said that she was "a little pitchy" and added that she seemed to be "overthinking" the song.<ref name="latimes">{{cite web|url=http://latimesblogs.latimes.com/showtracker/2012/03/american-idol-recap-the-top-10-take-on-billy-joel.html|title='American Idol' recap: The top 10 take on Billy Joel (Poll)|first=Amy|last=Reiter|work=[[Los Angeles Times]]|publisher=[[Gannett Company]]|date=March 22, 2012|accessdate=April 14, 2012}}</ref> Amy Reiter of ''[[Los Angeles Times]]'' noted that "her clear, crisp tone, crashed and burned on 'Honesty,' missing notes and losing her way".<ref name="latimes" /> Laura Prudom of ''[[The Huffington Post]]'' was mixed about her performance writing, "She was occasionally pitchy on this song, and seemed to be overthinking it in parts and allowing the song to overwhelm her... Unusually, she seemed both nasal and pitchy in the early parts of the performance... her choice of a pantsuit was completely baffling, since it made her look nearer 40 than 20."<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/laura-prudom/american-idol-recap-billy-joel_b_1371719.html|title='American Idol' Recap: The Top 10 Perform The Songs Of Billy Joel|work=[[The Huffington Post]]|first=Laura|last=Prudom|date=March 22, 2012|accessdate=May 30, 2012}}</ref> Later, during an interview, Cavanagh revealed that she had difficulties singing the song because she had never heard it before.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://content.usatoday.com/communities/idolchatter/post/2012/05/hollies-exit-interview-this-week-something-was-just-different/1|title=Hollie's exit interview: 'Something was just different'|work=[[USA Today]]|publisher=[[Gannett Company]]|first=Jayme|last=Deerwester|date=May 11, 2012|accessdate=May 30, 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/idol-worship/american-idol-hollie-cavanagh-323550|title='American Idol' Castoff Hollie Cavanagh Stands by Her Song Choice, Despite Jimmy Iovine's Criticism|work=[[The Hollywood Reporter]]|publisher=Prometheus Global Media|first=Michele|last=Amabile Angermiller|date=May 11, 2012|accessdate=May 30, 2012}}</ref>

==Beyonc<U+00E9> Knowles version==
[[File:Beyonce-2008 2.jpg|thumb|Beyonc<U+00E9> Knowles (''pictured; 2008'') covered "Honesty" for her album ''I Am... Sasha Fierce'']]
In 2008, American recording artist, [[Beyonc<U+00E9> Knowles]] re-recorded Billy Joel's version of the song for a [[compilation album]] of her former group [[Destiny's Child]], titled ''[[Mathew Knowles & Music World Present Vol.1: Love Destiny]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.allmusic.com/album/mathew-knowles-and-music-world-present-vol-1-love-destiny-r1416105|title=Mathew Knowles and Music World Present, Vol. 1: Love Destiny|publisher=Allmusic. Rovi Corporation|accessdate=December 20, 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.amazon.com/Mathew-Knowles-Music-World-Present/dp/B0018Q7IAA|title=Mathew Knowles and Music World Present, Vol. 1: Love Destiny|publisher=[[Amazon.com]]. Amazon Inc|accessdate=December 20, 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite album-notes|title=Mathew Knowles & Music World Present Vol.1: Love Destiny|albumlink=Mathew Knowles & Music World Present Vol.1: Love Destiny|artist=Destiny's Child|year=2008|authorlink=Destiny's Child|format=Compact Disc|publisher=Columbia Records}}</ref> The song was later included on the Platinum Edition of her third solo album, ''[[I Am... Sasha Fierce]]'' (2008).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://itunes.apple.com/au/album/i-am-sasha-fierce-platinum/id329220872 |title=I Am...Sasha Fierce (Platinum Edition) |publisher=[[iTunes Store]]. [[Apple Inc]] |accessdate=April 16, 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.allmusic.com/album/i-amsasha-fierce-platinum-edition-r1646969|title=I Am...Sasha Fierce <nowiki>[Platinum Edition]</nowiki>|publisher=Allmusic. Rovi Corporation|accessdate=August 24, 2011}}</ref><ref name="iam">{{cite album-notes |title=I Am... Sasha Fierce |albumlink=I Am... Sasha Fierce |artist=[[Beyonc<U+00E9> Knowles]] |publisherid=0088697417352 |year=2008 |format=Platinum Edition |publisher=[[Columbia Records]]}}</ref> Pip Ellwood of Entertainment Focus described Knowles' version of the song as a "turgid" ballad that doesn't "add too much to the record".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.entertainment-focus.com/music/articles/beyonce-i-amsasha-fierce-platinum-edition|title=Beyonce - I Am...Sasha Fierce Platinum Edition|first=Pip|last=Ellwood|publisher=Entertainment Focus|date=November 7, 2008|accessdate=August 24, 2011}}</ref> Serving as the sixteenth track to Knowles' platinum edition re-release of ''I Am... Sasha Fierce'', the song contrasts with previous tracks such as "Why Don't You Love Me".<ref name="allgigs.co.uk">{{cite web|url=http://www.allgigs.co.uk/view/review/4376/Beyonce_I_Am_Sasha_Fierce_Platinum_Album_Review.html|title=I Am... Sasha Fierce - Beyonc<U+00E9> Platinum Album Review|accessdate=August 24, 2011|first=Hannah|last=Spencer|publisher=Allgigs}}</ref> It showcases Knowles' "soulful" voice and "outstanding" vocal range as stated by Hannah Spencer of the website Allgigs.<ref name="allgigs.co.uk"/> Ken Bielen in his book ''The Words and Music of Billy Joel'' wrote, "Backed primarily by an electronic keyboard and an urban [[rhythm and blues]] arrangement, she stays faithful to the original ballad with a bittersweet vocal performance."<ref name="Bielen">{{cite book|url=http://books.google.mk/books?id=dFwV3oyy6Y8C&pg=PA131&dq=Honesty+beyonce+billy+joel&hl=en&sa=X&ei=6AxZT8S5KK-S0QWBooy9DQ&ved=0CDkQ6AEwAQ#v=onepage&q=Honesty%20beyonce%20billy%20joel&f=false|title=The Words and Music of Billy Joel|first=Ken|last=Bielen|page=131|year=2011|accessdate=March 8, 2012}}</ref> "Honesty" was performed during Knowles' concert at the [[Olympic Gymnastics Arena]] in Seoul on October 20, 2009 as part of her worldwide [[I Am... Tour]] (2009-10).<ref>{{cite video|people=Beyonc<U+00E9> Knowles|title=I Am... Tour|location=[[Olympic Gymnastics Arena]], Seoul, South Korea|date=October 20, 2009}}</ref> The song became very popular on the [[Gaon Chart|South Korea Gaon International]] charts, peaking at number two.<ref name="translate.google.com">{{cite web|url=http://translate.google.com/translate?hl=en&sl=auto&tl=en&u=http%3A%2F%2Fwww.gaonchart.co.kr%2F|title=Honesty Debuts At Number 2 In Korea|publisher=[[Gaon Chart]]|accessdate=June 14, 2010}}</ref> It became the ninth and one hundred and seventy third best-selling single in 2010 and 2011 in South Korea respectively.<ref name="korea2010" /><ref name="korea2011" />

